title: larry_foulke
body:
Ustio Air Force
6th Air Division
66th Air Force Unit
Galm 2 Larry "Pixy" Foulke

"This man was his buddy. And his enemy." 
-Brett Thompson

Galm team's number 2, wingman to [[Cipher_(ace_combat)|]] was a [[F-15 Eagle]] mercenary fighter pilot during the Belkan War in [[Ace Combat Zero]]. Earned the nickname "Solo Wing" because he flew back and landed his aircraft at base with one wing after returning from a skirmish. Being proud of that feat, he had the right wing on his plane painted red. During the war, he defected and joined the coupe movement of "A World With No Boundaries" aligned with Belka, Osea, and Sapin; while another pilot from Crow Team transferred in as Galm 1's wingman. After narrowly escaping death in the final fight against his former ally over the skies of Avalon Dam, a badly wounded Pixy dragged his body to a nuclear detonation site on Belkan soil where he was saved by the people who lived there. Many years later, Larry would join [[ISAF]] and fight on the front lines in the second Usean Continental War in [[Ace Combat 04]] as a ground soldier. He is in search of a world without borders, hoping to find the true meaning behind them. 

Voiced by Yuri Lowenthal

title: cipher_(ace_combat)
body:
Ustio Air Force 
6th Air Division 
66th Air Force Unit
Galm 1 “Cipher”

Flight leader of the Galm team and player character in [[Ace Combat Zero]]. His canon aircraft is a [[F-15 Eagle]] with part of its wings and vertical stabilizers painted a dark grey.

“Every time I flew with him his skill stood out. He was unstoppable. It didn't matter where the battlefield was, the man had complete trust in his own powers. He was born for battle, a demon lord who struck down all opposition. He'd pay no heed to the troubles of those who flew with him. Before long, everyone had taken notice of him. More and more would show up to watch him go off on sortie. Mercenaries or maintenance crew, it didn't matter. People wanted to burn his image into their memories. Hell, they weren't the only ones."

-[[Larry Foulke]] 

"The Demon Lord of the Round Table. A warrior who soared through the Belkan War, inspired both fear, and admiration. His presence filled the skies for but a few short months before he disappeared. Apart from that, nothing is known about him. I was never able to find out what kind of person he really was. But whenever they talked about him, they always had a slight smile on their faces. That perhaps, may be my answer."

-Brett Thompson

title: aim-7_sparrow
body:
The AIM-7 Sparrow (Air Intercept [[Missile]]) is an American, medium-range semi-active radar homing air-to-air [[missile]] operated by the [[United States Air Force]], [[United States Navy]], and United States Marine Corps, as well as other various air forces and navies. Sparrow and its derivatives were the West's principal beyond visual range (BVR) air-to-air [[missile]] from the late 1950s until the 1990s. It remains in service, although it is being phased out in aviation applications in favor of the more advanced AIM-120 AMRAAM.

The early Sparrow was intended primarily for use against larger targets, especially bombers and had numerous operational limitations in other uses. Against smaller targets, the need to receive a strong reflected radar signal made achieving lock-on at the [[missile]]'s effective range difficult. As the launching [[aircraft]]'s own radar needed to be pointed at the target throughout the engagement, this meant that in fighter-vs-fighter combat, the enemy fighter would often approach within the range of shorter-range infrared homing missiles while the launching aircraft had to continue flying towards its target. Additionally, early models were only effective against targets at roughly the same or higher altitudes, below which reflections from the ground became a problem.

A number of upgraded Sparrow designs were developed to address these issues. In the early 1970s, the [[royal_air_force|RAF]] developed a version with an inverse monopulse seeker and improved motor known as Skyflash, while the Italian Air Force introduced the similar Aspide. Both had the ability to be fired at targets below the launching fighter ("look-down, shoot down"), were more resistant to countermeasures, and were much more accurate in the terminal phase. This basic concept was then made part of the US Sparrows in the M model (for monopulse) and some of these were later updated as the P model, the last to be produced in the US. Aspides sold to [[China]] resulted in the locally produced PL10. The [[japan_self-defense_force|Japan Self-Defense Forces]] also employ the Sparrow missile, though it is being phased out and replaced by the Mitsubishi AAM-4.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: AIM-7 Sparrow":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AIM-7_Sparrow]

title: judo
body:
[b]Judo[/b] (柔道, [i]jūdō[/i], meaning "gentle way") is a modern [[martial_arts|martial art]], combat and olympic sport created in [[Japan]] in 1882 by Jigoro Kano (嘉納治五郎). 

Its most prominent feature is its competitive element, where the objective is to either throw or takedown an opponent to the ground, immobilize or otherwise subdue an opponent with a pin, or force an opponent to submit with a joint lock or a choke. Strikes and thrusts by hands and feet as well as weapons defenses are a part of judo, but only in pre-arranged forms (型, [i]kata[/i]) and are not allowed in judo competition or free practice (乱取り, [i]randori[/i]).

The philosophy and subsequent pedagogy developed for judo became the model for other modern Japanese martial arts that developed from koryū (古流, "traditional schools"). The worldwide spread of judo has led to the development of a number of offshoots such as Sambo and Brazilian jiu-jitsu. Judo practitioners are called judoka.

title: fgm-148_javelin
body:
The FGM-148 Javelin (AAWS-M) is a shoulder-fired American-made portable anti-tank [[rocket launcher|missile system]].  Its fire-and-forget design uses automatic infrared guidance that allows the user to seek cover immediately after launch, as opposed to wire-guided systems which require the user to guide the weapon throughout the engagement.  The system takes a top-attack flight profile against armored vehicles, attacking the usually thinner top armor, but can also make a direct attack.  The Javelin's tandem HEAT warhead is capable of defeating modern tanks equipped with Explosive Reactive Armor.

The system consists of three main components: the Command Launch Unit, the Launch Tube Assembly and the missile itself.  The reusable Command Launch Unit commonly referred to as a CLU (pronounced "clue") is the targeting component of the system. The CLU has three views which are used to find, target, and fire the missile and may also be used separately from the missile as a portable thermal sight.  The disposable Launch Tube Assembly has built in electronics and a locking hinge system that makes attachment and detachment of the missile to and from the Command Launch Unit quick and simple.

h4. See also

* [[NLAW]]
* [[Javelin (spear)]]

h4. External links

title: kokkuri-san_(game)
body:
Kokkuri-san is a Japanese game similar to a Western [[ouija]] board.  The name comes from a combination of the animal spirits that are called upon to answer the player’s questions; the kitsune (ko), dog (ku) and tanuki (ri). To play, the following is required: a 10 yen [[coin]], a [[pen]], a piece of [[paper]] and someplace to put the paper down on.

Players begin by writing "YES", "NO", the Japanese alphabet and a red [[torii]]. Players must place their fingers on the coin and invoke Kokkuri-san. Afterwards, the players are free to ask whatever question they want until they wish to dismiss the spirit.

The game must never be played alone or as a prank, finished halfway or end without dismissing the spirit and disposing of the pen, paper and coin. Players must also not take their finger off the coin until the game is over. Failure to do so will result in misfortune or death.

title: roadrunner_(animal)
body:
Latin (genus): [i]Geococcyx sp.[/i] 

Roadrunners are fast-running ground birds with long tails and crests. They are large, slender, with black-brown and white-streaked coloration and long legs, strong feet, and an oversized dark bill. The tail is broad with white tips on the three outer tail feathers. The bird has a bare patch of skin behind each eye; this patch is shaded blue to red.  

There are two species, found in the southwestern and south-central United States and Mexico, usually in the desert. Some have been clocked at 20-27mph.

title: do_335
body:
The Do-335 Pfeil ("Arrow") was a World War II heavy fighter built by the Dornier company for the German Luftwaffe. The inline dual-engine "push-pull" setup was much more efficient than standard side-by-side twin engine designs, such as found on the Messerschmitt [[bf_110|Bf-110]]. Armed with a 30mm Mk 103 cannon through the propeller hub and two 20mm MG151 cannons mounted near the wing roots, it followed the precedent set by fighters before it for carrying large anti-bomber cannons. Some variants also carried up to 1,000kg (2,200lb) of bombs in a doored bay in the center of the underside of the fuselage.

Though multiple prototypes were flown and its production priority was hastened by the "Jägernotprogramm":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergency_Fighter_Program, Allied bombings and corruption kept it from entering service.

h4. See Also:

* "Wikipedia Page":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dornier_Do_335

title: f4u_corsair
body:
A [[United States Navy]] carrier and [[United States Marine Corps|marine]] warplane used during WW2 and Korea. Originally meant to be a dogfighter but grew more into the role of ground attack as the wars progressed.

The Corsair is easily identified by its huge size- easily twice the size of the zero, something rather unusual for carrier-borne aircraft. Its propeller is the largest ever put on a single-seat fighter, measuring at 13 feet from tip to tip. Consequently its nose was so big that the craft was barred from service until pilots could be trained to land on a curved arc (in fact, this was what led to the Corsair being released for [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] use where they outmatched IJN aviators flying Zeroes). While there were two Navy squadrons that still flew Corsairs when they were first deployed, one soon switched to [[F6F Hellcat]] use while the other (VF-17 of [[Bunker Hill (Azur Lane)|]]) was removed from the carrier until November 1943.

It can also be identified by its gull wing, which swoops down before angling upward, giving the plane a unique silhouette and elegant appearance. This was done solely to keep the massive prop from striking the ground during takeoff and landing, but it also gave the plane uncommon dive and climb characteristics that pilots exploited, as well as a signature whistle during a dive.

Despite the Corsair's early troubles caused by its massive power and hog nose, pilots eventually adapted and it became highly successful, finishing the war with a kill ratio of 1-12 (in its favor).

h4. See also
* "Wikipedia: Vought F4U":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vought_F4U_Corsair]

title: tenebrism
body:
From the Italian [i]tenebroso[/i] — meaning dark, gloomy, mysterious — tenebrism describes a compositional technique in which some areas of an image are kept completely black, allowing other areas to be strongly illuminated, usually from a single source of light. It is distinct from chiaroscuro because there is no attempt to include forms in the darkness. [[Chiaroscuro]] is commonly employed to enhance the modelling of human figures, not to focus the viewer's attention or blacken whole areas of the canvas for dramatic effect. Thus it is not uncommon for both tenebrism and chiaroscuro to be used in the same canvas.

h4. See also

title: iroha_karuta
body:
[[Karuta (card game)|]] are Japanese playing [[card]]s with Portuguese origins. They are used in various card games.

Iroha Karuta is a matching game consisting of two decks with corresponding cards, [i]yomifuda[/i] (reading cards) and [i]torifuda[/i] (taking cards). The [i]torifuda[/i] cards are placed face up before the players. A referee draws from the [i]yomifuda[/i] deck and calls out their card. The players must compete with each other to take the corresponding [i]torifuda[/i] card. Whoever collects the most at the end wins.

Iroha Karuta decks consist of the 47 hiragana characters while other variations of the game may use poems or other art or literature.

h4. See also

* [[Karuta (card game)|]]
* [[Uta-Garuta]]

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Karuta":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karuta]

title: uta-garuta
body:
Uta-garuta is a Japanese card game played using [[karuta (card game)|]] cards. The game consists in 100 pairs of cards each associated with a classical poem, each composed of a [i]yomifuda[/i] and [i]torifuda[/i]. The [i]yomifuda[/i] contains the full text of the poem, while the [i]torifuda[/i] contains only the last phrase.

During the game, the torifuda cards are laid on the ground. On each round, the reader will read the poem from the yomifuda, and the players must try to find the corresponding torifuda card as quickly as possible. The player who collects the most torifuda cards wins.

Torifuda cards typically have a green border, and 14 letters of the poem laid on a grid (see: post #1431356)

The manga [[Chihayafuru]] is focused on players of uta-garuta.

h4. See also

* [[Iroha Karuta]]
* [[Karuta (card game)|]]

title: shiva_(housamo)
body:
A [[Tokyo Afterschool Summoners]] character.
Designed by [[Dai-xt]]

A Transient from Devaloka, a world that aims to perpetuate itself via a system of reincarnation. He is an earnest young monk who seeks to dedicate his life to the betterment of his physical and spiritual being. Together, his past, present, and future selves can open the seventh chakra to attain immeasurable physical prowess. It is said that the universe will come to an end when the third eye upon his forehead opens, so he strives to keep it shut. This requires him to bury the seething emotions within himself and display total abstinence. He knows that to unleash the power of his third eye is to unleash shakti, the cosmic source, and be transformed into his final form. He was once shot through the heart with an arrow of love and has been captivated by his obsession with the emotion ever since. He feels uneasy in the presence of a certain crocodilian individual because he is reminded of the beast that accompanied the one who shot the arrow.

title: yamato_kai_(kancolle)
body:
[[Yamato (Kancolle)|]]'s kai form (post #1578595), the main difference between this form and her base from is the presence of the idiom "Hirihoukenten" (非理法権天) on her single thighhigh.

It reflects one of the old philosophies in feudal Japan where foolishness (非) is not above sensibility (理), sensibility is not above law (法), law is not above authority (権), and authority is not above divinity (天).
The full idiom stands for "No Man Can Oppose the Emperor", and it was historically flown on Yamato's mainmast during Operation Ten-Go.

Another noticeable change is that she trades off her two 155 mm triple mounts attached on the hulls themselves for 25 mm triple AA guns.

title: mmorpg
body:
Short for Massively Multiplayer Online Role Playing Game. Computer Role Playing Games (RPGs) which feature gameplay elements of traditional RPGs, but take place in a persistent online virtual world populated with characters controlled by other human players.

MMORPGs are commonly associated with diehard devotees or socially inept people such as [[NEET]]s, due to the amount of time required just to become competent enough to play, and their use as a form of psychological escapism.

h6. Use on Danbooru

* Images which depict such a game being played.

title: bucket_chain_excavator
body:
A bucket chain excavator (BCE) is a large heavy equipment machine used in surface mining and dredging. BCEs use buckets on a revolving chain to remove large quantities of material. They are similar to [[bucket-wheel excavator]]s and trenchers. Bucket chain excavators remove material from below their plane of movement, which is useful if the pit floor is unstable or underwater.

h4. See also

* [[Excavator]]

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia - Bucket chain excavator":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bucket_chain_excavator]

title: bucket-wheel_excavator
body:
A bucket-wheel excavator (BWE) is a large heavy equipment machine used in surface mining.  They use a large wheel consisting of a set of continuous buckets to continually dig up material as the wheel turns.  They are some of the largest vehicles ever produced with the current record holder for BWEs weighing at 14,200 metric tons.

title: egusa_squadron_pilot_(kancolle)
body:
The [[fairy (kancolle)|]] representation of the Imperial Japanese Navy aviator Takashige Egusa (4 September 1909 - 15 June 1944).

In real life, Lt. Commander Egusa was part of [[Souryuu (Kancolle)|]]'s dive bomber squadron, hence the equipment's availability from [[Souryuu Kai Ni (kancolle)|remodeling]] Souryuu.
Surviving the battle of Midway, he was reassigned to shore-based bomber activities, ultimately killed in action flying a Yokosuka P1Y [i]Ginga[/i] bomber in the battle of Saipan.

title: iwamoto_squadron_pilot_(kancolle)
body:
The [[fairy (kancolle)|equipment fairy]] representation of the real-life IJN aviator LTJG Tetsuzou Iwamoto (15 June 1916 – 20 May 1955).

Resembles [[Zuikaku (Kancolle)|]] since he was assigned to her fighter squadron from Pearl Harbor up to the battle of the Coral Sea.
In real life, Tetsuzou Iwamoto was the highest scoring WW2 fighter pilot ace of the Pacific Theater, amassing 80+ kills flying A6M Zeroes. He was also capable of night carrier operation, a rarity in the IJN (as they never fully developed night carrier ops in the same way as the [[Royal Navy]] and US Navy did).

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia: Tetsuzou Iwamoto.":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetsuz%C5%8D_Iwamoto]

title: murata_squadron_pilot_(kancolle)
body:
The [[fairy (kancolle)]] representation of Shigeharu Murata (9 April 1909 - 26 October 1942), an Imperial Japanese Navy aviator.

Resembles [[Shoukaku (Kancolle)|]] due to the aviator's history below.

h4. History
Shigeharu Murata was a highly skilled torpedo bomber pilot who led the first attack wave on Pearl Harbor. Attacking from [[Shoukaku (Kancolle)|]] during the battle of the Santa Cruz Islands (October 26, 1942), his squadron heavily damaged [[Hornet (Kancolle)|]], who was already under attack by dive bombers. During the attack, however, Murata's plane was hit, prompting him to crash to Hornet and was killed in action.

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia: Shigeharu Murata.":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shigeharu_Murata]

title: kanno_naoe
body:
Kanno Naoe is a Witch of the [[502nd Joint Fighter Wing]], originating from Fuso and affiliated with the Fuso Imperial Navy. She is also known by the pet name of "Nao" (ナオ). Her familiar is the bulldog.

Naoe can be described, in one word, as Napoleonic; despite her small size, she bold and daring in the air, brash and sometimes belligerent socially. It's an attitude she forces on herself because of the war with the [[Neuroi]]: when her Witch abilities woke up, she roused herself by repeating the prayer: "to fight a Neuroi, one should have a ferocious personality". This attitude doesn't lend itself well to teamwork or cooperation, but under Flight Lieutenant [[Aleksandra I. Pokryshkin|Pokryshkin]] this is dampened somewhat, perhaps because she resembles an elder sister of Naoe's childhood, whom she remembers fondly.

Naoe is based on Japanese flying ace [[Kanno Naoshi]] (菅野直). One of his nicknames was Bulldog, Naoe's familiar is a reference to this. Besides that, he was also nicknamed "Destroyer" and "Yellow Fighter".

title: hank_anderson
body:
The human protaganist of [[Detroit: Become Human]]. Hank is a Detroit Police detective assigned to investigate the growing number of deviant androids and is ordered to work with [[connor_(detroit)|Connor]] over the course of his assignment. Hank is distrustful of androids following a previous incident and initially has a hard time getting along with Connor as a result. Whether this relationship improves or degrades depends on player actions while in control of Connor.

Hank is an older man with graying hair and a trimmed beard. He is usually seen in darker clothing and carries a [[revolver]] as a personal weapon.
other_names: ハンク・アンダーソン

title: markus_(detroit)
body:
One of the three protaganist androids in [[Detroit: Become Human]]. Markus was acquired by an older owner who purposefully instilled a sense of individuality in him, though it was ultimately a bloody break-in incident that resulted in him gaining sapience and becoming a deviant. Left for dead after being shot by responding Detroit Police officers, Markus would fall in with a group of deviant androids called "Jericho" and lead them into a revolution. Whether their uprising ends in peaceful or violent fashion depends on the player's actions with him and the other controllable characters.

Markus is a darker-skinned individual with short-cropped, dark hair and brown eyes, and is usually seen wearing a tan and gray overcoat above his normal android outfit.

title: kara_(detroit)
body:
One of the three main protagonist androids of [[Detroit: Become Human]]. Kara is an android meant for domestic housework purchased by an abusive owner. The stress from her treatment resulted in her becoming a deviant and running away along with her owner's daughter [spoiler]who is revealed to be an android as well[/spoiler]. The goal of the two is to escape into Canada, which has no laws concerning androids.

Kara has short, brown/blonde hair and blue eyes. Her base outfit is a black-and-white shirt and leggings, with the shirt indicating her model number (AX-400). Her outfit while attempting to blend into the human population includes a heavy vest to cover it up.

title: connor_(detroit)
body:
One of the principal protaganist characters of [[Detroit: Become Human]]. Connor is a model of [[android]] specialized in criminal investigations, assigned to a human partner named [[Hank Anderson]] following incidents in which androids went rogue and murdered their owners. In the course of his investigation, he can bond or break apart with Hank while having an influence on the outcome of a budding android revolution.

Connor is fair-skinned with dark hair and blue or silver eyes, in addition to having a legally-mandated LED above his right eye to indicate that he is an android. He usually wears a suit, with the jacket indicating his model (RK-800).

body:
Also known as a [i]Fireman's Carry Facebuster[/i], this [[wrestling]] move sees a [[wrestler]] lift an opponent up in a [[fireman's carry]] across their shoulders, then throw the opponent's legs out in front of them to spin them out, while simultaneously falling backwards or forwards, causing the opponent to land on their face and upper body.

title: ame-no-uzume-no-mikoto
body:
Ame-no-Uzume-no-mikoto (天宇受売命, 天鈿女命?) is the goddess of dawn, mirth and revelry in the Shinto religion of Japan, and the wife of fellow-god Sarutahiko Ōkami. She famously relates to the tale of the missing sun deity, Amaterasu Omikami. Her name can also be pronounced as Ama-no-Uzume.[1][2]

Amaterasu's brother, the storm god Susano'o, had vandalized her rice fields, threw a flayed horse at her loom, and brutally killed one of her maidens due to a quarrel between them. In turn, Amaterasu became furious with him and retreated into the Heavenly Rock Cave, Amano-Iwato. The world, without the illumination of the sun, became dark and the gods could not lure Amaterasu out of her hiding place.

The clever Uzume overturned a tub near the cave entrance and began a dance on it, tearing off her clothing in front of the other deities. They considered this so comical that they laughed heartily at the sight.[3] This dance is said to have founded the Japanese ritual dance, Kagura. [4]

Amaterasu heard them, and peered out to see what all the fuss was about. When she opened the cave, she saw her glorious reflection in a mirror which Uzume had placed on a tree, and slowly emerged from her hiding spot.

At that moment, the god Ame-no-Tajikarawo-no-mikoto dashed forth and closed the cave behind her, refusing to budge so that she could no longer retreat. Another god tied a magic shimenawa across the entrance.[5] The deities Ame-no-Koyane-no-mikoto and Ame-no-Futodama-no-mikoto then asked Amaterasu to rejoin the divine. She agreed, and light was restored to the earth.

Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto is still worshiped today as a Shinto kami, spirits indigenous to Japan.[6] She is also known as Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto, The Great Persuader, and The Heavenly Alarming Female.[7] She is depicted in kyōgen farce as Okame, a woman who revels in her sensuality

Having grown tired of Marisa constantly bringing home big hauls of books from the Voile Library, [[Patchouli Knowledge]] attempts to stop the incessant theft by stashing her books in her newly-created castle and hires several other characters to protect her palace. But Marisa, aided by Alice, sets out to defeat her friends before making a climactic raid on Patchouli's trap-laden castle to bring home another big haul of books.

This game is considered "one of the hardest games ever", since it is a clone of the Mega Man games with the Danmaku shooting tradition of the [[Touhou]] series.
